# Remark 3.4.3. 

In addition to the $\mathrm{D} \& \mathrm{C}$ decision rule presented earlier, several alternative decision rules can be considered to enhance prediction accuracy. These rules compare the discrepancies between predicted probabilities and cut-off values but take into account different scaling factors such as standard deviation, relative differences, and means. For instance, the following variations can be formulated:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \tilde{q}_{i, h j}-\hat{c}_{h j}=\max \left\{\frac{\tilde{q}_{i, h 1}-\hat{c}_{h 1}}{s\left(\tilde{q}_{h 1}\right)}, \frac{\tilde{q}_{i, h 2}-\hat{c}_{h 2}}{s\left(\tilde{q}_{h 2}\right)}, \frac{\tilde{q}_{i, h 3}-\hat{c}_{h 3}}{s\left(\tilde{q}_{h 3}\right)}\right\} \\
& \tilde{q}_{i, h j}-\hat{c}_{h j}=\max \left\{\frac{\tilde{q}_{i, h 1}-\hat{c}_{h 1}}{\hat{c}_{h 1}}, \frac{\tilde{q}_{i, h 2}-\hat{c}_{h 2}}{c_{h 2}}, \frac{\tilde{q}_{i, h 3}-\hat{c}_{h 3}}{c_{h 3}}\right\} \\
& \tilde{q}_{i, h j}-\hat{c}_{h j}=\max \left\{\frac{\tilde{q}_{i, h 1}-\hat{c}_{h 1}}{m\left(\tilde{q}_{h 1}\right)}, \frac{\tilde{q}_{i, h 2}-\hat{c}_{h 2}}{m\left(\tilde{q}_{h 2}\right)}, \frac{\tilde{q}_{i, h 3}-\hat{c}_{h 3}}{m\left(\tilde{q}_{h 3}\right)}\right\}
\end{aligned}
$$

where $m(q)$ represent the mean of the $q_{i}$, and $s(q)$ is the standard deviation of the $q_{i}$ which may improve the accuracy of predictions.
